ts importance in teaching and learning. Departing from the more traditional teacher-led mode of teacher–student communication, the dialogic approach is more egalitarian and focuses on the discourse exchange between the parties. Authors explore connections between dialogic pedagogy and sociocultural learning theory, and argue that dialogic interaction between teacher and learners is vital if instruction is to lead to cognitive development. The book also presents prosody as a critical resource for understanding between teachers and students, and includes some of the first empirical studies of speech prosody in classroom discourse.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aCommunication in education. 0aConversation analysis. 0aDialogue analysis. 0aPedagogical content knowledge. 7aEDUCATION / Educational Psychology.2bisacsh  aDialogic pedagogy .  aDialogism.  aDialogue .  aDiscourse analysis.  aEducational psychology.  aLanguage development.  aLanguage education.  aLiteracy .  aPedagogy .  aProsody .  aSociocultural learning theory.1 aBrinn, Michelle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDaniels, Harry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEsiyok, Julie Margaret, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKremer, Jean Baptiste, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMurakami, Kyoko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMurakami, Kyoko, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSkidmore, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSkidmore, David, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aZhao, Xin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook